"I hereby strongly suggest we do that!"

473
00:16:52,124 --> 00:16:53,363
- Hold on.
- He used vibrato.

474
00:16:53,364 --> 00:16:55,034
Why would he use vibrato?

475
00:16:55,534 --> 00:16:57,904
- Was it a musical?
- It sounded soulful.

476
00:16:58,134 --> 00:17:00,473
- I've never seen anyone do that.
- He practically sang.

477
00:17:00,474 --> 00:17:02,074
I think that's when my voice changed.

478
00:17:02,334 --> 00:17:03,673
When I was little, I had such a loud voice.

479
00:17:03,674 --> 00:17:06,513
Even when my parents were right next to me, I called them...

480
00:17:06,514 --> 00:17:09,383
- like this. "Mom! Dad!"
- Oh, my. I see.

481
00:17:09,384 --> 00:17:10,913
They would say I had a voice like a foghorn.

482
00:17:10,914 --> 00:17:13,184
They said my voice was too loud like I was shouting.

483
00:17:13,354 --> 00:17:14,813
But that was just my normal volume.

484
00:17:14,814 --> 00:17:17,484
"Mom! Dad!" This is just my normal volume.

485
00:17:18,684 --> 00:17:20,154
- You're not angry, are you?
- Are you angry?

486
00:17:20,254 --> 00:17:21,494
- You're not angry, are you?
- Why...

487
00:17:21,724 --> 00:17:23,824
- Is that you just calling them?
- Why would you throw a tantrum?

488
00:17:24,164 --> 00:17:25,663
- That's not the case.
- Why would you throw a tantrum?

489
00:17:25,664 --> 00:17:27,533
It's just my normal volume when I speak to them.

490
00:17:27,534 --> 00:17:30,034
- "Mom! Dad!" It's my normal volume.
- Really?

491
00:17:30,904 --> 00:17:32,063
How did your father answer?

492
00:17:32,064 --> 00:17:33,203
"Why?" Like this?

493
00:17:33,204 --> 00:17:37,004
My dad has a loud voice too. So he answers like this.

494
00:17:37,204 --> 00:17:38,774
- "Why, Seung Wan?"
- My goodness.

495
00:17:39,174 --> 00:17:40,374
"Why? What is it?"

496
00:17:40,544 --> 00:17:43,443
- She takes after her father.
- But my mom has a quiet voice.

497
00:17:43,444 --> 00:17:45,444
So she used to complain about our loud voices.

498
00:17:45,914 --> 00:17:48,154
- I thought all people could do it.
- I see.

499
00:17:48,614 --> 00:17:50,254
But it turned out that I had a rare talent.

500
00:17:50,854 --> 00:17:52,054
You mean, singing high notes?

501
00:17:52,254 --> 00:17:55,053
It's been a long time since I rock and rolled

502
00:17:55,054 --> 00:17:57,624
I thought everyone else could sing like I did.

503
00:17:57,764 --> 00:17:58,863
That makes sense. When Jong Seo was little,

504
00:17:58,864 --> 00:18:00,933
- there weren't many karaoke rooms.
- There was none.

505
00:18:00,934 --> 00:18:02,264
- Karaoke rooms?
- It must've been hard to compare.

506
00:18:02,364 --> 00:18:04,334
- When I was little?
- He must've sung in a reed field.

507
00:18:04,604 --> 00:18:06,003
- There were no karaoke rooms then.
- I don't remember.

508
00:18:06,004 --> 00:18:07,903
- He doesn't remember.
- He sang in a reed field...

509
00:18:07,904 --> 00:18:09,544
- or when the lightning struck...
- The war was in full swing.

510
00:18:09,904 --> 00:18:11,073
- because other people complained.
- I mean...

511
00:18:11,074 --> 00:18:12,673
- The war was going on, - He needed a quiet place.

512
00:18:12,674 --> 00:18:13,674
- so he couldn't go to karaoke.
- During the war...

513
00:18:13,675 --> 00:18:15,073
Was it when the March First Independence Movement happened?

514
00:18:15,074 --> 00:18:17,244
- How could anyone go to karaoke?
- He sang into his chopsticks.

515
00:18:17,344 --> 00:18:18,644
It was during the Imo Military Rebellion.

516
00:18:19,684 --> 00:18:21,414
He sang into his chopsticks instead of a mic.

517
00:18:21,514 --> 00:18:23,954
Are you born with the ability to hit high notes?

518
00:18:24,124 --> 00:18:26,254
I believe that natural talent is also necessary.

519
00:18:26,354 --> 00:18:28,594
- But you must develop the talent.
- Improving the skills you lack?

520
00:18:28,794 --> 00:18:30,064
When I went to karaoke,

521
00:18:30,364 --> 00:18:33,593
I sang songs of musicians like Kim Kyung Ho...

522
00:18:33,594 --> 00:18:35,794
- You sang my songs too, right?
- I sang many of your songs.

523
00:18:36,304 --> 00:18:38,204
I set the key to the maximum range for every song I sang.

524
00:18:38,334 --> 00:18:40,303
- You raised the key even higher?
- That key suited my voice better.

525
00:18:40,304 --> 00:18:41,603
- No way.
- I see.

526
00:18:41,604 --> 00:18:42,873
You raised the key...

527
00:18:42,874 --> 00:18:44,103
- of Jong Seo's songs?
- No way.

528
00:18:44,104 --> 00:18:46,343
- It suited my voice better.
- Kyun Sung is amazing.

529
00:18:46,344 --> 00:18:47,643
People go crazy about his performances.

530
00:18:47,644 --> 00:18:50,284
- I know that. I watched him sing.
- I'm not saying I was talented.

531
00:18:50,584 --> 00:18:53,854
I had no choice because of my shortcomings.

532
00:18:54,184 --> 00:18:56,083
- You can't sing low notes?
- That's correct.

533
00:18:56,084 --> 00:18:57,784
It's hard for me to sing low notes.

534
00:18:58,684 --> 00:18:59,893
I can hit much lower notes now.

535
00:18:59,894 --> 00:19:02,194
Kyun Sung, the original key of Jong Seo's songs is too low to you.

536
00:19:02,324 --> 00:19:03,893
- It's too low to you.
- It feels low to me.

537
00:19:03,894 --> 00:19:05,024
- What?
- Right?

538
00:19:05,094 --> 00:19:07,893
One of Jong Seo's songs has extremely high notes.

539
00:19:07,894 --> 00:19:09,334
- Right. My songs have high notes.
- So...

540
00:19:09,534 --> 00:19:12,834
But the original key of most of his songs...

541
00:19:12,934 --> 00:19:14,604
- It's high.
- is a bit low to me.

542
00:19:15,034 --> 00:19:16,344
A higher key suits my voice better.

543
00:19:16,574 --> 00:19:18,373
- That's incredible.
- You can handle the original key,

544
00:19:18,374 --> 00:19:20,043
- but a higher key feels easier?
- I need it to be higher.

545
00:19:20,044 --> 00:19:21,614
- Jong Seo, what's happening?
- Really?

546
00:19:21,914 --> 00:19:23,543
- Sorry?
- What would you call this?

547
00:19:23,544 --> 00:19:24,944
His vocal range is so high...

548
00:19:25,044 --> 00:19:26,584
I'd call this an abomination.

549
00:19:26,984 --> 00:19:28,814
- An abomination?
- Yes.

550
00:19:29,824 --> 00:19:32,283
Jong Seo's vocal range is higher than many other singers.

551
00:19:32,284 --> 00:19:33,894
- His vocal range is very high.
- It's very high.

552
00:19:34,154 --> 00:19:35,553
Soo Geun, you can't sing high notes, right?

553
00:19:35,554 --> 00:19:37,263
- Right. We used to sing together.
- I can't sing low notes.

554
00:19:37,264 --> 00:19:38,593
- I can't sing low notes.
- You can't sing low notes?

555
00:19:38,594 --> 00:19:39,833
- I was unable to sing low notes.
- That's so interesting.

556
00:19:39,834 --> 00:19:41,334
I had zero range in the low and medium notes.

557
00:19:41,564 --> 00:19:42,593
I hated that,

558
00:19:42,594 --> 00:19:45,203
so I abandoned my high notes and practiced solely...

559
00:19:45,204 --> 00:19:46,433
on low and medium notes,

560
00:19:46,434 --> 00:19:48,003
which helped me get this voice.

561
00:19:48,004 --> 00:19:49,333
(Ended up with a solid voice)

562
00:19:49,334 --> 00:19:52,403
Did anyone start with a low-to-middle tone...

563
00:19:52,404 --> 00:19:55,173
and then reach high notes by practicing?

564
00:19:55,174 --> 00:19:56,243
Can you reach high notes...

565
00:19:56,244 --> 00:19:57,313
- by practicing?
- I did too.

566
00:19:57,314 --> 00:19:58,543
- Really, Jae Hwan?
- When...

567
00:19:58,544 --> 00:20:00,853
- I just started singing, - Yes?

568
00:20:00,854 --> 00:20:04,524
the highest I could reach was second octave G to F sharp.

569
00:20:04,784 --> 00:20:06,193
- But...
- That's still high enough.

570
00:20:06,194 --> 00:20:09,664
I overcame that limit when taking part in the show.

571
00:20:09,864 --> 00:20:11,123
How high can you reach now?

572
00:20:11,124 --> 00:20:12,593
- Right now...
- Now, I can reach...

573
00:20:12,594 --> 00:20:14,093
the third octave C to D.

574
00:20:14,094 --> 00:20:15,163
The third octave C to D?

575
00:20:15,164 --> 00:20:17,063
- Isn't that really high?
- What a huge jump.

576
00:20:17,064 --> 00:20:18,563
- To think it's possible.
- Those notes...

577
00:20:18,564 --> 00:20:19,573
- are really high.
- I don't know...

578
00:20:19,574 --> 00:20:20,574
what third octave C means.

579
00:20:20,774 --> 00:20:22,943
- The third octave C to D.
- How high can you go, Kyung Hoon?

580
00:20:22,944 --> 00:20:24,603
- How high?
- My songs...

581
00:20:24,604 --> 00:20:27,544
end around the second octave B-flat, like "Coward."

582
00:20:28,444 --> 00:20:30,183
(From "Coward" by Buzz)

583
00:20:30,184 --> 00:20:36,823
(Even if I cry and whine like a child who lost his way)

584
00:20:36,824 --> 00:20:40,654
(2nd octave B-flat parts)

585
00:20:40,854 --> 00:20:43,893
At times, I do sing up to the third octave C, but it's really tough.

586
00:20:43,894 --> 00:20:46,093
- Did you say the third octave C?
- Yes, C.

587
00:20:46,094 --> 00:20:47,163
When I was in the band,

588
00:20:47,164 --> 00:20:48,194
I reached that note while doing the dishes.

589
00:20:49,704 --> 00:20:50,804
Humming.

590
00:20:51,164 --> 00:20:52,164
That easily?

591
00:20:52,165 --> 00:20:55,033
(The 3rd octave C is perfect to hum.)

592
00:20:55,034 --> 00:20:57,843
Jong Seo, did you cook for yourself back then?

593
00:20:57,844 --> 00:21:00,273
- I did. I was broke.
- By the way...

594
00:21:00,274 --> 00:21:01,773
- While doing the dishes?
- Jong Seo.

595
00:21:01,774 --> 00:21:04,214
- I have a question for Jong Seo.
- Goodness.

596
00:21:04,644 --> 00:21:06,013
Can someone...

597
00:21:06,014 --> 00:21:07,153
- Yes?
- with a low, husky voice...

598
00:21:07,154 --> 00:21:08,183
reach high notes...

599
00:21:08,184 --> 00:21:09,213
- Apparently, yes.
- through practicing?

600
00:21:09,214 --> 00:21:11,083
- To a certain note.
- Yes, to a certain note.

601
00:21:11,084 --> 00:21:13,493
Use your vocal cords to a minimum.

602
00:21:13,494 --> 00:21:15,693
- Depend less on your vocal cords.
- Okay.

603
00:21:15,694 --> 00:21:18,493
Bring out the high notes through breathing. Push the sound out.

604
00:21:18,494 --> 00:21:20,533
Keep practicing, and you'll become good at it.

605
00:21:20,534 --> 00:21:22,833
I'm currently in the process of raising my notes up.

606
00:21:22,834 --> 00:21:24,663
- Are you still practicing?
- Yes.

607
00:21:24,664 --> 00:21:25,933
- I have a feeling...
- Can you raise the notes even now?

608
00:21:25,934 --> 00:21:27,204
- I can reach higher.
- Unbelievable.

609
00:21:28,004 --> 00:21:30,404
After all, your vocal cords are made of muscles.

610
00:21:30,604 --> 00:21:33,143
You gain muscle and lift heavier weights...

611
00:21:33,144 --> 00:21:35,213
- if you keep working out.
- True.

612
00:21:35,214 --> 00:21:36,583
Your vocal cords are the same.

613
00:21:36,584 --> 00:21:37,783
How do you practice?

614
00:21:37,784 --> 00:21:40,213
I have vocalization lessons 2 to 3 times a week.

615
00:21:40,214 --> 00:21:42,653
- You attend lessons even now?
- Yes, even now.

616
00:21:42,654 --> 00:21:43,953
The more I go to my lessons,

617
00:21:43,954 --> 00:21:46,223
- the better I get at singing...
- Continuously?

618
00:21:46,224 --> 00:21:48,593
- as my vocal cords become stronger.
- Who teaches you...

619
00:21:48,594 --> 00:21:50,464
when you're already that good, Wendy?

620
00:21:50,764 --> 00:21:52,623
A vocalization instructor.

621
00:21:52,624 --> 00:21:53,963
There are many instructors...

622
00:21:53,964 --> 00:21:54,964
- who theoretically know...
- Exactly.

623
00:21:54,965 --> 00:21:56,133
how to vocalize well.

624
00:21:56,134 --> 00:21:57,703
Even Michael Jackson...

625
00:21:57,704 --> 00:21:59,263
- had a teacher.
- Yes.

626
00:21:59,264 --> 00:22:00,703
- True.
- Even Stevie Wonder.

627
00:22:00,704 --> 00:22:02,534
Not all instructors are better...

628
00:22:03,244 --> 00:22:05,003
- than their students.
- Totally.

629
00:22:05,004 --> 00:22:06,873
- Of course.
- Some are better at teaching.

630
00:22:06,874 --> 00:22:10,583
Out of all my basketball coaches since childhood,

631
00:22:10,584 --> 00:22:12,083
no one was better than me.

632
00:22:12,084 --> 00:22:13,084
(A player greater than the team)

633
00:22:13,085 --> 00:22:14,883
- As expected.
- For real?

634
00:22:14,884 --> 00:22:16,384
The one and only in the world.

635
00:22:16,554 --> 00:22:18,583
- He's the only one.
- No.

636
00:22:18,584 --> 00:22:19,723
- It wasn't about you.
- Listen.

637
00:22:19,724 --> 00:22:22,054
- He's just showing off.
- I...

638
00:22:22,294 --> 00:22:23,963
- He just wants to show off.
- I'm not...

639
00:22:23,964 --> 00:22:25,564
the best player in the world.

640
00:22:26,164 --> 00:22:28,793
What I meant was there are instructors...

641
00:22:28,794 --> 00:22:31,503
who aren't better than their students.

642
00:22:31,504 --> 00:22:33,303
- Yes.
- Coaches are different.

643
00:22:33,304 --> 00:22:35,203
- Exactly.
- Correct.

644
00:22:35,204 --> 00:22:36,503
The interviewer who hired me as a comedian wouldn't have been...

645
00:22:36,504 --> 00:22:38,344
- funnier than me.
- No.

646
00:22:38,604 --> 00:22:40,744
I'm sure the interviewer was a boring person.

647
00:22:41,374 --> 00:22:43,313
- That's how it is.
- Exactly.

648
00:22:43,314 --> 00:22:44,844
Why are you acting like it has nothing to do with you?

649
00:22:45,114 --> 00:22:47,983
Ho Dong, were your ssireum coaches...

650
00:22:47,984 --> 00:22:49,283
better than you?

651
00:22:49,284 --> 00:22:50,923
- Yes, they were better.
- Those coaches...

652
00:22:50,924 --> 00:22:52,384
(Yes, they were better.)

653
00:22:52,724 --> 00:22:54,123
(Cutting him off fast)

654
00:22:54,124 --> 00:22:55,423
- Who were they?
- As expected.

655
00:22:55,424 --> 00:22:57,193
- Amazing.
- Who were the coaches?

656
00:22:57,194 --> 00:22:58,593
- Nice one.
- Who were better than you?

657
00:22:58,594 --> 00:23:01,694
I always felt I wasn't good enough and had room to improve,

658
00:23:01,894 --> 00:23:05,103
so I stuck to my coaches' training and worked hard.

659
00:23:05,104 --> 00:23:07,304
- I was an obedient player too.
- Right.

660
00:23:07,434 --> 00:23:08,904
But my point is that...

661
00:23:09,134 --> 00:23:10,203
I was better...

662
00:23:10,204 --> 00:23:11,643
- at basketball than them.
- Right.

663
00:23:11,644 --> 00:23:14,674
It's a different sport. My coaches were good at ssireum.

664
00:23:14,844 --> 00:23:17,844
Jeong Hee, weren't you a vocal teacher...

665
00:23:18,014 --> 00:23:20,153
- for Jo Kwon and SUNYE?
- I was.

666
00:23:20,154 --> 00:23:22,613
In the past, SBS had a show...

667
00:23:22,614 --> 00:23:24,123
to rear gifted children.

668
00:23:24,124 --> 00:23:25,423
- Yes, I remember.
- Yes.

669
00:23:25,424 --> 00:23:27,553
- When Kwon was a kid.
- It was a show hosted...

670
00:23:27,554 --> 00:23:28,953
by Park Jin Young.

671
00:23:28,954 --> 00:23:31,793
I was one of the vocal teachers.

672
00:23:31,794 --> 00:23:35,564
Back then, Rain was the dance teacher.

673
00:23:35,734 --> 00:23:37,534
We've known each other since then.

674
00:23:37,764 --> 00:23:39,733
After the show,

675
00:23:39,734 --> 00:23:42,433
SUNYE, Kwon, GSoul, and HyunA...

676
00:23:42,434 --> 00:23:46,474
were cast by the company.

677
00:23:46,614 --> 00:23:49,314
We practiced together at the company...

678
00:23:49,514 --> 00:23:52,343
and have been friends all along.

679
00:23:52,344 --> 00:23:55,454
Honestly, I may be good at this field,

680
00:23:55,684 --> 00:23:57,154
but there are those...

681
00:23:57,554 --> 00:23:59,123
- who are much better than I am, - Totally.

682
00:23:59,124 --> 00:24:00,523
just like athletes.

683
00:24:00,524 --> 00:24:01,853
It's a war between pros.

684
00:24:01,854 --> 00:24:04,593
You'll most likely beat everyone.

685
00:24:04,594 --> 00:24:07,193
But is there someone who always gets on your nerves?

686
00:24:07,194 --> 00:24:08,663
Someone you acknowledge.

687
00:24:08,664 --> 00:24:10,664
- No one?
- He's not a rival or anything,

688
00:24:11,534 --> 00:24:12,834
but it'd be Yim Jae Beom.

689
00:24:14,304 --> 00:24:16,473
I joined Sinawe earlier...

690
00:24:16,474 --> 00:24:18,273
- than Jae Beom did.
- You totally did.

691
00:24:18,274 --> 00:24:20,774
Back then, I was an amateur...

692
00:24:21,314 --> 00:24:23,913
and left the band, not participating in that long.

693
00:24:23,914 --> 00:24:26,514
Yim Jae Beom appeared out of the blue,

694
00:24:26,654 --> 00:24:28,214
and I saw him practice.

695
00:24:28,514 --> 00:24:30,523
He had something I didn't have.

696
00:24:30,524 --> 00:24:34,294
Jae Beom has a solid low-to-middle tone.

697
00:24:35,224 --> 00:24:39,023
The emotions and vocal tone are out of this world.

698
00:24:39,024 --> 00:24:40,663
It was a real shocker.

699
00:24:40,664 --> 00:24:42,664
- Was it?
- Yes, I was genuinely shocked.

700
00:24:42,894 --> 00:24:46,333
That motivated me to study more about low and medium notes.

701
00:24:46,334 --> 00:24:48,604
It's a rumor that I heard, but apparently,

702
00:24:49,134 --> 00:24:51,674
Jae Beom couldn't hit the high notes like I did.

703
00:24:51,844 --> 00:24:53,413
- You had different tones.
- We admired...

704
00:24:53,414 --> 00:24:56,174
what we each didn't have and worked hard.

705
00:24:56,944 --> 00:24:59,213
To think the one who gets on his nerves is Yim Jae Beom.

706
00:24:59,214 --> 00:25:00,654
I know, right?

707
00:25:01,054 --> 00:25:03,723
When it comes to me, it'd be Lee Young Hyun of Bigmama.

708
00:25:03,724 --> 00:25:05,223
- I get it.
- Right?

709
00:25:05,224 --> 00:25:06,993
In high school, I attended...

710
00:25:06,994 --> 00:25:07,994
a practical music academy...

711
00:25:07,995 --> 00:25:09,423
- for college.
- I see.

712
00:25:09,424 --> 00:25:11,363
And there Lee Young Hyun was.

713
00:25:11,364 --> 00:25:13,893
It was really loud when I went...

714
00:25:13,894 --> 00:25:15,663
- to enroll.
- Is that so?

715
00:25:15,664 --> 00:25:18,203
Someone was singing Whitney Houston's song.

716
